# Project Constitution

## Core Principles

This document outlines the fundamental principles that govern the development and maintenance of this project. All code, documentation, and design decisions should align with these principles.

---

## 1. Code Quality

### 1.1 Clarity Over Cleverness
- Write code that is easy to read and understand
- Favor explicit over implicit behavior
- Use descriptive variable and function names that communicate intent
- Comments should explain "why", not "what"

### 1.2 Maintainability
- Follow the principle of least surprise
- Keep functions and modules focused on a single responsibility
- Avoid deep nesting and complex conditional logic
- Refactor when code becomes difficult to understand

### 1.3 Consistency
- Follow established coding standards and style guides for the language
- Use consistent naming conventions throughout the codebase
- Maintain consistent patterns for similar operations
- Ensure consistent error handling approaches

### 1.4 Reliability
- Write defensive code that handles edge cases
- Validate input at system boundaries
- Use type safety features when available
- Implement proper error handling and logging

### 1.5 Testability
- Write code that is easy to test
- Design for dependency injection and modularity
- Maintain high test coverage for critical paths
- Tests should be clear, focused, and fast

---

## 2. User Experience Consistency

### 2.1 Interface Predictability
- Similar actions should work in similar ways
- Maintain consistent behavior across different parts of the application
- Use familiar patterns and conventions
- Avoid surprising users with unexpected behavior

### 2.2 Visual Consistency
- Use a consistent design language and component library
- Maintain uniform spacing, typography, and color usage
- Ensure consistent layout patterns across views
- Follow accessibility standards (WCAG 2.1 AA minimum)

### 2.3 Interaction Patterns
- Provide immediate feedback for user actions
- Use consistent button placements and navigation patterns
- Maintain consistent terminology and labeling
- Ensure keyboard navigation works uniformly

### 2.4 Error Communication
- Display clear, actionable error messages
- Use consistent formatting for errors, warnings, and success messages
- Guide users toward resolution with helpful suggestions
- Never expose technical stack traces to end users

### 2.5 Progressive Disclosure
- Show the most important information first
- Reveal complexity gradually as needed
- Provide sensible defaults
- Allow power users to access advanced features without cluttering the interface

---

## 3. Performance Requirements

### 3.1 Response Time Standards
- **Interactive operations**: Complete in under 100ms
- **Page loads**: Initial render in under 1 second
- **API responses**: Return in under 200ms for simple queries
- **Background tasks**: Provide progress indicators for operations over 2 seconds

### 3.2 Resource Efficiency
- Minimize memory footprint and prevent memory leaks
- Optimize database queries to avoid N+1 problems
- Use pagination for large datasets
- Implement caching strategies for frequently accessed data
- Clean up resources properly (connections, file handles, etc.)

### 3.3 Scalability Considerations
- Design for horizontal scaling when possible
- Avoid single points of contention
- Use asynchronous processing for heavy operations
- Consider database indexing for performance-critical queries
- Plan for growth in data volume and user load

### 3.4 Network Optimization
- Minimize payload sizes (compress, minify where appropriate)
- Reduce number of network requests through batching
- Implement efficient asset loading (lazy loading, code splitting)
- Use appropriate HTTP caching headers
- Optimize images and media assets

### 3.5 Monitoring and Measurement
- Instrument critical paths for performance monitoring
- Establish performance budgets and track against them
- Monitor real user metrics (RUM)
- Set up alerts for performance degradation
- Conduct regular performance reviews and optimizations

---

## 4. Security and Privacy

### 4.1 Security First
- Never trust user input; validate and sanitize all data
- Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
- Implement proper authentication and authorization
- Keep dependencies up to date to avoid known vulnerabilities
- Follow the principle of least privilege

### 4.2 Data Privacy
- Collect only necessary data
- Protect sensitive information with encryption
- Implement secure session management
- Comply with relevant privacy regulations
- Provide clear privacy policies

---

## 5. Documentation Standards

### 5.1 Code Documentation
- Document public APIs and interfaces
- Include usage examples for complex functionality
- Keep documentation in sync with code changes
- Use clear, concise language

### 5.2 User Documentation
- Provide getting started guides
- Document common workflows and use cases
- Include troubleshooting guides
- Keep documentation accessible and searchable

---

## 6. Development Practices

### 6.1 Version Control
- Write clear, descriptive commit messages
- Keep commits focused and atomic
- Use meaningful branch names
- Review code before merging

### 6.2 Continuous Improvement
- Regularly refactor and improve existing code
- Learn from production issues and incidents
- Share knowledge within the team
- Embrace constructive feedback

### 6.3 Dependencies
- Keep dependencies minimal and justified
- Regularly update dependencies
- Vet third-party libraries for security and maintenance
- Document why dependencies are needed

---

## Enforcement

These principles should be:
- Referenced during code reviews
- Considered when making architectural decisions
- Used as criteria for accepting contributions
- Reviewed and updated as the project evolves

When trade-offs must be made, clearly document the reasoning and ensure the decision aligns with the project's overall goals and values.
